<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="433" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,789]" pageId="12" pageNumber="433">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,692,717]" pageId="12" pageNumber="433">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[621,797,693,716]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Evinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="433" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrospinus">
<emphasis box="[621,797,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="433">E. macrospinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in coloration and the shape of the subgenital plate, but differs in having the clypeal suture arcuate, and the middle section of the aedeagal shaft straight in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1215,764,789]" pageId="12" pageNumber="433" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,789]" box="[199,1215,764,789]" pageId="12" pageNumber="433">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,764,789]" pageId="12" pageNumber="433">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet refers to the flattened medial section of the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
